		<div id="main">
			<h2 id="what-is">What <em>is</em> settingsctl?</h2>
			<p>settingsctl is a utility that aims to provide a common interface to
			desktop settings (think power, appearance, <abbr title="etcetera">etc</abbr>.) in different desktops, which usually have differing methods to
			configure these.
			</p>
			<p>This was also the aim of the <a href="https://portland.freedesktop.org/doc/xdg-settings.html">xdg-settings project</a>.
			But that <a href="#why-not-xdg-settings">failed</a>.</p>

			<h2 id="what-settings-available">What settings are available?</h2>
			<p>See the <a href="documentation/settings.html">Available settings</a>.</p>

			<h2 id="how-to-use">How do I use this?</h2>
			<p>See the <a href="documentation/tutorial.html">tutorial</a>.</p>

			<h2 id="how-to-install">How do I install this?</h2>
			<p>See the <a href="documentation/install.html">installation guide</a>.</p>

			<h2 id="what-language">What language is this written in?</h2>
			<p>Python 3.</p>

			<h2 id="why-not-xdg-settings">Why not xdg-settings?</h2>
			<p>
				<ol>
					<li>It's not been updated since about 2011<sup><a href="http://manpages.ubuntu.com/manpages/en/man1/xdg-settings.1.html">[1]</a></sup></li>
					<li>It has only <em>two</em> settings: default web browser and URI scheme handlers<sup><a href="https://portland.freedesktop.org/doc/xdg-settings.html">[2]</a></sup></li>
				</ol>
			</p>
